{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645089","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645089"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:12:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:12:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18081"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18081"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.55,0.24,0.07,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10795"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75378"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10795"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18081"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60887"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5699"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25149"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25960"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26005"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75378"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 92-year-old woman with advanced dementia, bed-bound for two years, develops severe pneumonia. She has minimal conscious awareness, requires full nursing care, and has recurrent aspiration. She has no Advance Care Directive. Her family insists on full intensive care treatment including mechanical ventilation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the ethical principle that should guide decision-making in this case?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Patient autonomy takes precedence over medical judgement","Treatment that cannot achieve meaningful benefit should not be provided","Family wishes override medical considerations","Resource allocation determines treatment decisions","Life preservation outweighs quality of life concerns"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe principle that \u003Cstrong\u003Etreatment that cannot achieve meaningful benefit should not be provided\u003C/strong\u003E is most appropriate here. Given the patient\u0027s severe cognitive impairment, minimal conscious awareness, and poor baseline function, mechanical ventilation would not improve her quality of life or provide meaningful benefit, making it medically futile. In addition, prolonging the inevitable will only add to the family\u0027s distress. Careful counselling with the family will be crucial in this patient\u0027s management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatient autonomy takes precedence over medical judgement\u003C/strong\u003E - While patient autonomy is important, healthcare professionals are not obliged to provide treatments that cannot benefit the patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFamily wishes override medical considerations\u003C/strong\u003E - Although family input is valuable in decision-making, they cannot demand treatments that doctors determine to be futile.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EResource allocation determines treatment decisions\u003C/strong\u003E - Although responsible resource use is important, the primary consideration in futility is the lack of benefit to the individual patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELife preservation outweighs quality of life concerns\u003C/strong\u003E - The goal of medical care is to benefit patients, not merely to prolong physiological functions without meaningful quality of life.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMedical futility focuses on whether an intervention can achieve a meaningful outcome for the patient, not just whether it can temporarily sustain physiological functions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Medical futility occurs when treatment provides no meaningful benefit or has no realistic chance of achieving the desired physiological effect.","Futile treatments consume healthcare resources without improving patient outcomes or quality of life.","The determination of futility requires consideration of both quantitative (probability of success) and qualitative (value of outcome) factors."],"references":["Mandal J, Ponnambath DK, Parija SC. Bioethics: A brief review. Trop Parasitol. 2017;7(1):5-7. doi:10.4103/tp.TP_4_17","Varkey B. Principles of Clinical Ethics and Their Application to Practice. Med Princ Pract. 2021;30(1):17-28. doi:10.1159/000509119"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60887"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18081"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60887"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T17:52:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-29T17:53:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10795"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75378"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}